          "body": "The chapter is structured around a commission: Zion is herself made the *herald of good news* (40:9, *bāśar* — the verb that becomes the noun *euangelion* in the LXX). The content of her proclamation is one sentence: *Here is your God!* (*hinneh elohekem*). Two pictures of this God follow back-to-back. **Verse 10**: the LORD God comes *with might*, with His arm ruling for Him, bringing reward and recompense — the sovereign warrior arriving in power. **Verse 11**: like a shepherd He tends His flock, gathers the lambs in His arm, carries them in His bosom, gently leads the nursing ewes — the tender shepherd of the weak. The same *arm* (v. 10's ruling arm, v. 11's gathering arm) does both. This is the chapter's central revelation: the God who is unimaginably powerful is also unimaginably tender, and *both* are aspects of the same coming."
