          "body": "The middle section is a sustained rhetorical assault on every god that is not YHWH. Through six *mi* (who) questions and two *to whom will you liken* challenges, Isaiah piles up images of God's incomparability: He measures oceans in His palm, weighs mountains in scales (v. 12); He needs no counselor (vv. 13-14); the nations are a drop in a bucket (v. 15); even Lebanon's cedars and beasts cannot constitute a worthy burnt offering (v. 16); rulers are reduced to nothing by a single breath (v. 23-24); the stars are led out by number and called by name (v. 26). In the middle of this argument Isaiah inserts the idol-polemic (vv. 18-20) — a craftsman casts a metal idol, the impoverished worshiper picks rot-resistant wood, and the goldsmith must make sure the thing *will not totter*. The absurdity is the argument: the God who weighs mountains cannot be represented by an object that must be steadied so it does not fall over."
