          "body": "After twenty-six verses of theology, the chapter finally names its pastoral target. Israel has been saying — perhaps quietly, perhaps bitterly — *my way is hidden from the LORD, and the justice due me escapes the notice of my God* (40:27). This is the despair of exile: God has stopped noticing, my case has been forgotten, the suffering has gone on too long for there to be a watching Father. Isaiah's response is not to deny the suffering but to recalibrate the theology. *Do you not know? Have you not heard?* (v. 28) — the same God who calls each numbered star by name (v. 26) cannot have lost track of your way (v. 27). The cure for despair is not changed circumstances but a recovered vision of who God is. The chapter's whole architecture — heralds, comfort, incomparability, idol-mockery — exists to make verse 27 impossible to maintain."
