        "excerpt": "Comfort, O comfort My people, says your God. Speak kindly to Jerusalem… A voice is calling, Clear the way for the LORD in the wilderness.",
        "body": "The chapter opens *in medias res* — without preamble, without an oracle-formula, without identifying the human speaker. We hear only YHWH commissioning unnamed heralds: *comfort, comfort My people*. The doubled imperative (*nachamu nachamu*) is emphatic Hebrew syntax — not *please comfort* but *comfort, yes truly comfort!* The audience is plural; this is a corporate prophetic commission. And the relational vocabulary is dense: *My people... your God*. The covenant bond, ruptured by exile and judgment in chapters 1-39, is unilaterally re-asserted by God in the chapter's first breath. Whatever else exile has done, it has not unmade the covenant.\n\nThe grounds of the comfort are three completed transactions (40:2). *Her warfare has ended* — the *tsava* word can mean military service or hard labor; the exile's appointed time is over. *Her iniquity has been removed* (*ratsah* — to be accepted as paid in full, the same root used of accepted sacrifice in Leviticus). *She has received from the LORD's hand double for all her sins* (*kephel*) — a debated phrase. The most likely sense is not that Israel suffered twice what she deserved (which would impugn divine justice) but that she received *the full measure* of disciplinary judgment, the fold-back equivalence between sin and consequence. The discipline is finished.\n\nThen a new voice breaks in (40:3-5): *A voice is calling, Clear the way for the LORD in the wilderness; make smooth in the desert a highway for our God*. The image is of a royal road being prepared for a king's arrival — valleys raised, mountains lowered, the rugged terrain leveled. Historically, this is the highway of return from Babylon. But all four Gospels read these verses as fulfilled in John the Baptist preparing the way for Messiah (Matthew 3:3; Mark 1:2-3; Luke 3:4-6; John 1:23). The exilic return becomes the typological pattern for the coming of Christ. The climax of the herald's announcement is v. 5: *then the glory of the LORD will be revealed, and all flesh will see it together; for the mouth of the LORD has spoken*. The chapter's eschatological horizon is total — every human being will see the manifest *kavod*.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nachamu nachamu* — the doubled imperative is the most emphatic form Hebrew offers; the only comparable opening is the seraphic *qadosh qadosh qadosh* of Isaiah 6:3. *Kephel* (double) is etymologically connected to folding — the same root that gives *kaphal* (to double over). The *kavod* (glory) that will be revealed is the same weighty presence that filled the temple at its dedication (1 Kings 8:11) and that Isaiah himself saw in chapter 6."
